                    android:text="THIS BOOK IS DESIGNED TO PROVIDE ACCURATE INFORMATION ON THE SUBJECTS COVERED."
                    android:textSize="16dp"
                    android:textColor="@color/white" />
                <TextView
                    android:layout_marginTop="10dp"
                    android:layout_width="match_parent"
                    android:layout_height="50dp"
                    android:text="General Guidelines in Answering Interview Questions"
                    android:textAlignment="center"
                    android:paddingTop="20dp"
                    android:textSize="20dp"
                    android:textColor="@color/white"
                    android:fontFamily="sans-serif-condensed-medium"
                    />
                <TextView
                    android:layout_width="match_parent"
                    android:layout_height="match_parent"
                    android:layout_marginLeft="12dp"
                    android:layout_marginRight="10dp"
                    android:fontFamily="@font/didact_gothic"
                    android:paddingTop="15dp"
                    android:text="Everyone is nervous on interviews. If you simply allow yourself to feel nervous,\n you\'ll do much better. Remember also that it\'s difficult for the interviewer as well. In general, be upbeat and positive. Never be negative.\nRehearse your answers and time them. Never talk for more than 2 minutes straight. \nDon\'t try to memorize answers word for word. Use the answers shown here as a guideonly,\n and don't be afraid to include your own thoughts and words.\n To help you rememberkey concepts, jot down and review a few key words for each answer.\n Rehearse your answers frequently, and they will come to you naturally in interviews."
                    android:textSize="18dp"
                    android:textColor="@color/white" />
                <TextView
                    android:layout_marginTop="10dp"
                    android:layout_width="match_parent"
                    android:layout_height="70dp"
                    android:text="Find out what people want, than show them\n how you can help them get it"
                    android:textAlignment="center"
                    android:paddingTop="20dp"
                    android:textSize="19dp"
                    android:textColor="@color/white"
                    android:fontFamily="sans-serif-condensed-medium"
                    />
                <TextView
                    android:layout_width="match_parent"
                    android:layout_height="match_parent"
                    android:layout_marginLeft="12dp"
                    android:layout_marginRight="10dp"
                    android:fontFamily="@font/didact_gothic"
                    android:paddingTop="15dp"
                    android:text="Find out what an employer wants most in his or her ideal candidate,\n then show how you meet those qualifications. In other words, you must match your abilities, with the needs of the employer.\n You must sell what the buyer is buying. To do that, before you know what to emphasize in your answers, you must find out what the buyer is buying...\n what he is looking for. And the best way to do that is to ask a few questions yourself. You will see how to bring this off skillfully as you read the first two questions of this report.\n But regardless of how you accomplish it, you must remember this strategy above all: before blurting out your qualifications, you must get some idea of what the employer wants most.\n Once you know what he wants, you can then present your qualifications as the perfect “key” that fits the “lock” of that position. \n • Other important interview strategies:\n • Turn weaknesses into strengths (You\'ll see how to do this in a few moments.)\n • Think before you answer. A pause to collect your thoughts is a hallmark of a thoughtful person."
                    android:textSize="18dp"
                    android:textColor="@color/white" />
